{"cursor":"4620","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn geometry, a 'line segment' is a part of a line that is bounded by two\ndistinct end points, and contains every point on the line between its end\npoints. Examples of line segments include the sides of a triangle or square.\nMore generally, when the end points are both vertices of a polygon, the line\nsegment is either an edge (of that polygon) if they are adjacent vertices, or\notherwise a diagonal. When the end points both lie on a curve such as a circle,\na line segment is called a chord (of that curve).\n","linknr":191,"url":"Line_segment","recorded":1362689182,"links":65,"instances":["geometry","geometry","geometry","mathematics","geometry","mathematics","geometry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Elementary geometry","Linear algebra"],"headings":["In real or complex vector spaces","Properties","In proofs","As a degenerate ellipse","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Segment_definition.svg/250px-Segment_definition.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Fotothek_df_tg_0003359_Geometrie_%5E_Konstruktion_%5E_Strecke_%5E_Messinstrument.jpg/220px-Fotothek_df_tg_0003359_Geometrie_%5E_Konstruktion_%5E_Strecke_%5E_Messinstrument.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/3/4/134676911181af05d24d406f16edf587.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/0/b/f0b01fe0a1eec87c634584ac0694fb71.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/1/2/11258fa7f33e01a97f78ba558cf5c862.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/2/9/329817ada78defd7321c0691889cae1f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/1/1/2110cfa36e30573db0322a9bcae3b7a2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/2/9/329817ada78defd7321c0691889cae1f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/1/f/a1fd49f304c1094efe3fda098d5eaa5f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/